A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers it a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only identified 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It was in this spirit that a majority of American governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This has increased since the November 2010 elections, adding 675 new Republican representatives in 26 States.
Accordingly, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced in 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day, and withdraw citizens with a judicial record from their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first State to make such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other States.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, it often costs more than $100 to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID card.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to be voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID card issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote the cards issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no State required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favour the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican legislators sponsored legislation abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to electors wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 brought the registration rate of new voters down by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have enacted laws in five other States aimed at reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were Afro-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
The same was true of the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, white voters who formed 76% of voters accounted for only 46% of voters voting in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The United States Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious objective to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the States that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to state with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
