Higgs boson decorated
The announcement of the likely discovery of Higgs' boson created a whole stir last summer and for cause.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, just that.
And then, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of the matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it is much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data released this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain.
Let's just assume it's the Higgs, because the odds of being wrong seem thin, and let's see what this is about.
There is, in this lower world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you'll hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting grossly in some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens named Fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, moreover) The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would in some way be related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all beasts as exotic as we might believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disadvantages" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, a bit like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disadvantage" is born an electromagnetic wave (of light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "power bearers".
More stable field
The same goes for Higgs' boson, which is the difference between it being another field, the Higgs field, which has to be "dangered" for this boson to appear.
However, this field of Higgs is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it must be reached with very, very high energies, somewhat as if it were a frozen pond whose only a very big rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and the mass.
It is not all particles, nor all materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, it is not all particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (such as photon, hold) do not have.
Now, what can you "bring" all this research, ask Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to look at any differences between the observations and predictions of the MS.
In fact, there are many who wish very much that they could be found, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "physical new" and close some holes in the Model.
This one, we must say, still has enormous shortcomings, not proposing any explanation for gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-ups!).
But we haven't found any such deviations at CERN until now.
Impacts
The impact of this research on Mr. and Mrs. All-World's daily life is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no such research.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in the Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work would trigger.
They were interviewing scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already been told by physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -, initially the laser was seen rather as a "Labo gadget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his optical work.
This sensor, although not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die...
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
In this essential area, however, much remains to be done.
The Devoir tried to look closer.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating him had left him a two-year break.
"They had given me five years to live, I made seven years," he said, half-fig half-raised, lying in his bed at the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois, from Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents it from going alone to the toilet, and even from eating alone.
Attached in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even comes to smile, talks to the strangers who deal with him, bring him his drugs, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
" During our life, we learn that a man is standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' house.
Returning to the child's stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability to accept regression," he notes.
For, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a life expectancy of up to three months.
At this stage, the "team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "conscious and stifled".
But the disease made me discover my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
" I have no more wishes in life," she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
However, in the next few days, she is expecting a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers are given care of the body and food aid.
It's palliative care that we give when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 people.
It's very little when we know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the home's doctors.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, we will agree to provide mouth care to brandy or Pepsi, as requested.
Diabetes will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of the daily life.
Last night, we had a beer served to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
" We help relatives as much as patients, " says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but do not resemble each other.
Alongside an old 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family assembly in the courtyard, well-shut in his pillows while being trinated in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two young children, after having tried everything to survive.
" For six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45, " worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to ease suffering when a patient has reached the terminal phase of his or her life, whether at home, at the hospital or in a care home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Société de care palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that causes several physicians specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by the tops of palliative care, including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in an emergency, in great pain, without doing what is necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients are only asking to die because they don't get the proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists crave on their patients until the last day, despite the worst predictions.
Helen Richard's survival expectations were already minimal when she abandoned proven chemotherapy.
When I announced to my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, did she tell me.
Yet she told me I was finished!
No all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who ask to die thank the caregivers for not having accessed their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care at the Society for Palliative Care at Home in Greater Montreal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of their lives, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which means sleeping the patient until the time of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unstressed patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Sick people who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die. "
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me," that means "I want to be relieved."
