The Facebook social network has also developed this kind of system.
But each time a central authority controls and treats trade.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account book depositors, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the way of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and whose winner, sort of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file hacking, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "take" the whole.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other knots easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any changes would change the footprint.
If, to fraud, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this award is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, leaving the margin of...
The challenge is also raised at each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
"The fault used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But the cash also has this defect.
Weight actors like Wikipedia refuse gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of the bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "giant balances" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also the author of an educational book on this currency, believes much in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but he uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come back cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement in merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They simply communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who ensures that thousands of users are available.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to take, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered to be high, in the event of the success of this currency.
