A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, it has decided to play its va-tout.
Taking everyone in court, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this House two more months to complete its work.
For the next two years Egypt has relied on a provisional text, several times amended which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic deliriousness", continuing to "trace his word" and to "peetinate the law".
On the side of his supporters, it is assured that this is a way of ending the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the challenge rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote results from the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "You either vote for my text or I keep the full powers", they are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent Assembly, by a large majority Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals were missing the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to put forward their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added to the haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles have been voted on.
Indeed, commentators enjoyed the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the constituent's pendulum was poorly resolved.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, article 2 finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the "establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a pledge of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the Liberals replied, who saw only a stroke of communication there.
For they believe that the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include section 220, which confers an advisory role on Al-Azhar University, in particular with respect to verifying compliance with the Sharia law.
According to Egypt's specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the premies of a theocracy."
The fears of the Liberals are further exacerbated by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not olemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" temper Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes "that there can be ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from the religious vocabulary.
It refers to "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And in the future, the question might arise as to how competent civil judges are to decide on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of its extended powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by human rights associations.
The latter also voice their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticid.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, there is no longer any mention of the protection of women, says Heba Morayef, Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
The support of the Head of State will march them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the centre of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of Bible truths, modern comfort and a wild nature.
Argomenty i Fakty has chosen five great reasons to visit Israel.
Go to worship holy places
Make yourselves indispensable: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone entering these "baptismal backgrounds" will be touched by the divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of Jesus' miracles: where water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on water, where he calmed down the storm, or where fishing was miraculous.
It was in this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
The believers go through the Rue de la Souffrance or the Via de Croix (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the pretoria), where the trial took place, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Onction and to the tomb.
This is where the Christian center of the world is, a symbol of the salvation of mankind.
According to the Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations, which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave small words with prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Massada fortress, a former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mount Hermont, which hosts many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
The country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that really are worth turning around.
First of all: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or manuscripts of the Dead Sea, discovered in the caves of the Desert of Judea, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also to be seen: the Art Museum of Tel-Aviv.
The paintings of impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are mainly exhibited.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of mouldings of visitors and overseers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures of Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
The entrance is free and donations are forbidden.
The fifth museum is the Museum of the Holocaust or Memorial of Yad Vashem, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
You then hear the names of Jewish children and the names of countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned here.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not fall below 21° while the air temperature can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
Blue water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who can't swim.
The landscapes surrounding it are surrealistic beauty.
Here we come to make a treatment based on salt water, lemon, curative sludge and to cure various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of Antiquity
They are kept by the old town of Tel-Aviv, Jaffa, on the edge of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Persée saved the beautiful Andromede, with whom he lived here a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk in narrow alleys that bear the name of the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, destiny will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet young married people who have come to take photo sessions from all Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, King Herod's city, you can walk in the Roman theatre, "conquer " the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Ponce Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Note to tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable in shekels (now $1 equals 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday night to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop their activity.
And the workweek starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafés, restaurants and hotels serve only homemade food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also humous, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, balls of wet chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-nourished cats who walk the high air.
We can see them sleeping at night on the roofs of parked cars.
These felines love the places passing and do not refuse to be spoiled.
Car rental varies according to the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of the figures
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
