While MPs and human rights activists are controversial about what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since 1 December, a law has entered into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian examination.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language, as well as the history of Russia and the foundations of law, will have to be validated.
We will need to validate his language skills in Russian to obtain and renew his work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or degrees of education prior to the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the auspices of the Russian Language Institute Pushkine, the University of Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the State University of St Petersburg and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to pass examinations in all cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already asked the question in the press many times: what is it going to give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service respond, which will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the Russian Federal Migration Service office in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, on the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in a crowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and paper and will have to go between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they are taken their passport, and they do not receive the intended salary," confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the Work of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, Officer!
However, many citizens of the republics of Central Asia who wish to come and earn money in Russia trust that they do not only know the language of the country where they wish to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow only a fair primary education.
In fact, their families don't even have anything to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people go out and earn money as soon as the opportunity comes.
It's hard when you don't know the language, trust them.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will only be for migrants with legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live illegally in Russia.
"Welcome or defend you from entering"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles rubles.
And then we can get a false recording quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have registration, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 roubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," told journalists Oumed Khuchkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan.
"Be quick, don't hurt and buy yourself a beautiful piece of art"
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration papers of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by Federal Migration Service employees.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for anything: each migrant who hoped to do so would facilitate the task of examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is twice and a half more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The representatives of power and human rights defenders agree that the short-term objective is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper tips".
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the examination at first time the time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian arms carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether they are shooting at weddings or killing organised by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to prohibit the use of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age of obtaining the permit to carry weapons from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Combating Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Arms Act would be introduced into the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "closing the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various firing centres, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered with the police, while 1,168 thousand crimes were registered during the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that strengthening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from supplying themselves with the black market.
According to them, we can find today in Moscow any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
