Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed it participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, Poland's road to outer space began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to A. Šternfeld's conference at Warsaw's Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde book entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagator of the world-renowned astronaut, his contribution has been rewarded in particular by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters on the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925 a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the drain.
The only known information about this raisin is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the documents retained that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research has stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpedoa powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects aimed at military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all rocket technology projects were conducted by the interim scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work on aviation was published in the Polish press, thanks to Polish astronaut society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problememe, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aviation.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company dedicated to astronomy.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish astronautic society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international astronautic federation (created in 1951) and, as early as autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He retained his position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This 1800-metre rocket had a length of 80 cm and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A and, during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 metre long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket was developed during the period 1962 - 1965, following the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litre, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litre and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 litre.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR National Committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on the Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Miroslav Hermaszewski pilot became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision raised in public opinion a lively discussion.
It is certainly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means concretely that the different economic entities and national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with a frantic financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) create a pressure on prices.
The following meaning should be put into effect: a producer strives to import low-priced goods to resist economic competition by " making the price of the competitor " more expensive, in order to remove a greater share of the market and thus increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying cheaply, or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the State's social burdens necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifys the complete unwillingness of gentlemen to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is at such a point of public awareness that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in different economies a situation in which the governments of different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account the social collapse.
This is reflected mainly in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the diktat of private capital prices, particularly in the area of wages.
This is due to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and to the restriction of employees' rights in the field of labour law.
This results in increasing poverty and widening the gap between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, there have been for years public food distribution points for poor people who cannot afford their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is forced to pay an additional fee to achieve the minimum living standard.
Such a scandal, for example, has been brought up to date in the case of employees working as assistants to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the Member States of the south of the EU undoubtedly create a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to live with poverty wages, in the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
Here we have to ask ourselves the following question: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will go from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, a Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to Latin America as a whole.
Liberal theory and the media state that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the led economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the State cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even today, does not, according to its own selfish interests, govern politics and by the same, the whole State.
The answer to this question is certainly yes.
The evidence is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby in all States.
This results in a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of bills to law firms closely related to industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
The entire power does not come from the people, as declared by the Western constitutions, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalist-oriented democracies are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "the crisis of the Roman empire in the time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State was long in delicacy and the functions were attributed by violence.
The bribes, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and the swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The under-tables and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with voices already sold" ... ... "The honest people were not seeking any functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls". ... 'We really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that we had to choose a energetic man" ... It is true that Appianos had in mind Pompey, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interests of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
Today, as in the past, the result is an unprecedented decadence of elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look at the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the present state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises that we are now witnesses to, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and internally, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
