The movie Argo: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamist students attacked the American Embassy of Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate stirs up a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated journeys, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make an impression on the filming of a science-fiction film.
Gender combination
The plan of exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requires Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is on the one hand a political thriller designed realistically but also a "caper moie", the story of a successful coup, of a treasuries - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres follow: sequences of documentary-style Tehran (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photographs, these same situations have been transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
Lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in restarting his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his actor's play ceased to elicit ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark cop "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that does not take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets during the reconstruction of real events; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, a history page is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too many actions to too many places
The director had to be content with a subject that actually offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It does well, it sometimes adds certain elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing track are quite pulled by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events to too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from that, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with a moderate interest, appreciating the performance and retro style of the 1970s.
He leads the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a history still, in a certain way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the trick.
