The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that the real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince themselves, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected book mountain - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it does very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one else willingly goes to one of these curly libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing to do with the gates of Rotterdam, has a fairly special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back a few neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty little painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get back to statistics: building a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam architect's office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of buildings full of spirit and often cynical, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a sneezing on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking, disconcerting and raising their shoulders, Maas, the facet, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and finished his speech supported by activist arguments by a: "common honey!"
Here she is, my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, or, as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million-euro mountain came up from land.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office, and a few buildings and houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the book mountains received the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this small, dull town, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of a horrifying uglyness, whose white facades invite to think that they shelter a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado from the book under cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open to you when you tread the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant reverbs speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs, and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books, and books.
"Normally, the library beams are located along the façade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We completely altered the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been conveniently arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes muddy, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, one millimetre thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we save time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimetres.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic " (KPL) changes its colour and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pots figs.
They create an atmosphere, but they contribute mainly to maintaining the ideal level of air humidity in the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in the field of ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is set by geothermal temperature.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass facade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic informatician, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already here, too.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" by Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, during the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids of the library that was not yet fully garnished (today, it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I think our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
Thus MVRDV has reached the master discipline that is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new literary history page.
Even if it may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status in the United Nations.
But then she chose forbearance.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but not to be too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 insurrection in Libya, Germany had also chosen forbearance in the vote on the establishment of an air-exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to say defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still taunting to find that role, but they're on their way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position vis-à-vis the Middle East conflict and forbearance in the United Nations vote?
Germany has first important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive factor in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing forbearance in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I think that the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has shown that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem so.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overjoying Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think that makes it any easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore enter into a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my view, Germany will assume a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Is Germany playing a major role on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it always difficult to assume leadership roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still faces difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look at, for example, the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make it any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to deal with very diverse neighbors and opinions, and it's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is diminishing, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're just less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Assistant Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Mark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially filed in China, but it has nothing to do with the original company.
The trademark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd win a cause.
