Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorragia (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Pubis lice and gall belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhage often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contacts between men are responsible for at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhage and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
In young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections concern young people aged 15 to 25 years.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure has increased from 1.967 in 2001 to 3.698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has decreased.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth over the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white loss, low-ventre pain, and the appearance of buttons and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect to 100%.
The reason for this is that pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close body contact.
The experts therefore recommend that any person who often changes sexual partners should undergo regular examinations.
Most rapidly detected STIs can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
