The hardest trade in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mules
For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by carrying the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas from the earth's guts solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulphur rocks, which weigh about 70 kilos in total, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters up to the peak of the volcano that culminates at 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle-like angle, keeping balance and measuring their steps to not stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who fell mortally in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, there is a path between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets painfully, they walk the 3 kilometers up to the balance that a mining company has installed a bit underground at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents euro) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to 10,000 rupees (83 cents euro) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (EUR 3.8) on each trip," says Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would gain in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", says the porter who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulphur has already begun to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work for another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
This friendly, intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wooden mask with other carriers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulphur does not stop rising at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
