Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas), became known worldwide by the leading role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of cancer complications, according to a family release sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his dear home town of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved the most again," the family said.
Larry's family and his close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who interpreted her wife's role in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said her press attaché, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all those who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I'm gonna miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life in full," Gray said in a statement.
The doctors had diagnosed a liver cirrhosis with Larry Hagman in 1992 and he had recognized that he had drunk a lot for many years.
In 1995, he had been detected with a malignant liver tumor and had been transplanted.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of my dreams" broadcast by the NBC channel from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also played in two comedies that remained short of time in the air, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles at the cinema are roles well received by critics in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which the character of Hagman is almost murdered, generated speculations around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in an episode of November 1980, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had brought together 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had pregnant her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but others also had reason to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man, but with a charismatic smile: an dishonest entrepreneur and an infidel husband who was trying to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "This is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, recalled this Friday of Hagman as a man "great, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
