A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a lecture on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hook: the end of the "great count" of the Maya calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal gulf that some have nicknamed "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of the end of time thought that the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé to his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker provides the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human conduct.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, the professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to teach again, in case the world does not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which does not leave students any choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," said Restall.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," said Restall about his course for high-level students, composed of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who were asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at the University of Rutgers-Camden.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in psychology and infirmary, claims to have watched all apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone one teacher, told us to believe in the end of the world on December 21.
"Our first project dealt with the Maya prophecy, and somehow we discredited it," says Julie Zegle, a senior student in Temple, 21 years old and from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world, it's only a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an anxiety linked to the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back to several centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has led to the growth of these speculations.
"In other places in the world, people don't think about it," he says.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that there were classes here on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophically about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many told us that they thought they'd go to "end of the world" parties.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
